{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958062701/0313.xml":{"full_text":"\u20acEDEMATO\nQe\n\n8\nAFL\n2-CIO s\nC\n17\ng\nQe\nrmnu0/-0\n\u2018OusmmAO\n/I\nf/\nOfficial Newspaper Of\nToledo Industriel\nUnion Council\nTOLEDO UNI\nON JOURNAL\nTHE\nN L Y L A|\nNE\nPE\nA\nB\nED EVER\nWEEK IN TOLEDO\n4\n12788/6,\n\u201c8 49 2 c <9 4 s :6\n\nRi\nX**\nit\n2\n222\nppwns\n2%\ny4e g\u2019w\nrhat\nZ\n\u2022*Y7Y,740Wg\n2ow/WSSauooidc\nwkk wrbodiSik\noodedtkatott\n2\n\nVOL. 18, NO. 26\nPublished By Organized Labor\n425 Winthrep St. m 0kM\nTOLEDO, OHIO, FRIDAY, JUNE 27,1858\n\u00bbA\u00bbVMI Pue. ce.\nTOLEDO\no\nMail Delivered To Homes\nOf Over 31,000 Subscribers\nFrom 120 Area Plants\nInquiring\n\nReporter\n\"Will your next auto be a larger or smaller\none than your pretent car?**\n(Asked at Spicer Manufacturing Division, Dana\nCorp.)\n$6\nPatterson\nWierszewski\nEd Wierszewski, 3916 Hazel\nhurst: \u201cSmaller. With the coat of\ncars and gas going up, I would\nprefer to get a good economical\ncar to drive. I\u2019m only getting 12\nmiles to the gallon with my\npresent car. I\u2019m going to make\nit a station wagon this time.\u201d\nJ. O. Patterson, 826 Ford St.,\nMaumee: \u201cI\u2019m going to switch\nto cheeper-driving cars They\ngive me as good a ride as a\nheavy car. I am planning to\nchange from General Motors\ncars anyway because of the way\nGM has been treating its work\ners.\nWhaley\nGary\nEd Whaley, 4846 Packard: '1\ndrive a medium size car, a 1954\nDeSoto .now, and I think my\nnext car will also be in the me\ndium size class. Gas economy\nisn\u2019t too important to me, nor\ndo I get a comfortable enough\nride in a small car. On the other\nhand, I don\u2019t want to have to\nenlarge my garage, or worrying\nabout parking, with a big car. In\nany case, I\u2019m going. to stick to\nAmerican-made cars.\u201d\nC. E. Gary, 915 Indiana Ave.:\n\u201cI think I\u2019ll stick to medium\nsize cars. I don\u2019t believe I can\ndo any better in a smaller car,\nDeGroff\n4*\n-4.4\n4\naesly\nPrice\nMeeting to Work For Metropolitan\nCounty-Type Government Set Here\nGroups which have expressed\nan interest in modernizing coun\nty government by adopting a\nhome rule charter for Lucas\nCounty have been invited to be\nrepresented at a meeting sched\nuled for 4 p.m. Tuesday (July\n1) in the Toledo Public Library.\nPurpose of the meeting is to\nbring together and inform in\nterested parties of the county\ncharter issue which will be sub\nmitted to county voters in No\nvember of this year, said Char\nles J. Cole, Toledo Municipal\nLeague president.\n\u201cLucas County voters will\n6 have the opportunity in Novem\nber to take the first step toward\ngiving this metropolitan county\na government designed to meet\nthe needs of its citizens in the\nmid-20th century,\u201d Mr. Cole ex\nplains.\nCounty government is now\norganized along lines designed\nfor rural counties of the last\ncentury and is not equipped to\nhandle efficiently the many\nfunctions of a modern urban\ncounty, a research memorandum\nby the Municipal League points\nout.\nTo Consider 2 Paints\nThe Municipal League\u2019s letter\nof invitation to the July 1 meet\ning indicates two major points\nto be considered:\nand my gas mileage is good,\nenough\u2014about 20 miles to the\ngallon.\u201d\nCharles DeGroff, 1630 Jer\nmain Dr* \u201cI like big cars for\ntheir comfort and luxury, and\nbecause I do a lot of driving.\nIt\u2019s worth the extra cost to me.\nNo, I don\u2019t find parking any\nproblem, either, not with power\nsteering.\u201d\nHorace \u201cCarly\u201d Price, 7810\nJackman: \u201cI\u2019m going to a small\ner car. I think their quality and\nride are as good as a bigger1,\ncar, and they cost considerably:\nless to buy and to drive. The\nprice of cars has .been getting\nso out of hand I might consider\ncalling for an investigation if I\nam elected to the Michigan state\nlegislature.\u201d\nChubner\nGrandowicz\nLarry Chubner, 438 Melrose:\n\u201cI\u2019ve owned both big cars and\nsmall ones, but all in all I pre\nfer the smaller autos. They\u2019re\neasier to handle, cheaper to buy\nand drive, and just as comfort\nable as the big ones.\u201d\nMartin Grandowicz, 10 East\nCrawford St.: \u201cCars are getting\ntoo big these days. Fm going to\nstay with the smaller ones, al\nthough I don\u2019t want one of the\nsmall foreign makes which are\ncrowded and uncomfortable.\u201d\nBrown\n4\ntez\n\n$e\ncia\n4.\nKeller\n\n\n\n\nPaul Brown, 3510 Hazelhurst:\n\u201cI might go for the big cars if\nI could afford it, but frankly,\nI don\u2019t have that kind of money.\nAnyway, the smaller cars have\nplenty of room and comfort as\nfar as I\u2019m concerned.\u201d\nLeVerne Keller, 2014 Brus\nsels: \u201cI\u2019ll take a smaller car. I\nnot only can\u2019t afford the bigger\ncars, but I prefer a car which\nisn\u2019t a gas hog.\u201d\n1. Informing the voters of\nthe facts about the county\ncharter question possibly\nthrough the formation of a\nbroadly representative citi\nzens committee.\n2. A method of selecting\ncandidates for positions on the\ncounty charter commission.\nInvited to the meeting are rep\nresentatives of\nthe\nboard of\ncounty commissioners, the City\nof Toledo and other municipali\nties, township officials and both\npolitical parties.\nOthers invited include labor\ngroups, the Toledo Area Cham\nber of Commerce, the Toledo\nIndustrial Development Council,\nthe League of Women Voters\nand both candidates for county\ncommissioner this fall, Ned\nSkeldon and A. G. Spieker.\nNeed Simple Majority\nThe Municipal League has\nearlier suggested that the origi\nnal county charter should be\nconfined to reorganization of\nthe form of county government\nalong modern lines, so that the\ncharter could be adopted by a\nsimple majority vote in the\ncounty.\n\u201cExperience elsewhere has\nindicated that trying to do too\nmuch in the charter\u2014to re\norganise county government\nand to give it broad new pow\nJ&L Gives\nSUBChecks\nTo 4 Here\nThe first known payments of\nSupplemental Unemployment\nBenefits negotiated in a UAW\nplant in Toledo went this week\nto four laid-off workers at the\nJones Laughlin Steel Con\ntainer Division here.\nThe four will receive a batch\nof ten checks totaling $485,\nJ&L Unit Chairman Ted Mo\ndrowski reported. Payments\nwill be today.\nThe benefits are going to em\nployees who have exhausted\ntheir benefits under the Ohio\nUnemployment Compensation\nlaw, a company official said.\nReceiving the benefits will be\nWilma Wood, five checks; Wil\nma Batchfield, two payments;\nReva Coller, one, and Irene Cie\nsielski, two.\nNegotiated In Good Faith\nPlant Superintendent N. C.\nMurray noted that Jones\nLaughlin had negotiated Sup\nplemental Unemployment Bene\nfits in good faith.\n\u201cIt was our intention to make\npayments under the negotiated\nterms to all eligible employees\nas soon as possible. We hope\nthese SUB payments will be a\nreal stimulant to the economy,\nand above all, will give needed\naid to our people.\"\nJ&L began building up a\nSUB fund for their employees\non Aug. 1, 1956. Payments from\nthe fund were to begin the fol\nlowing August but were not al\nlowed as the result of a ruling\nby James Tichenor, Bureau of\nUnemployment Compensation\nadministrator.\nHis ruling was overturned by\na court decision in Youngstown\nwhich ruled that simultaneous\nI payments could be made under\nthe s td t e law. An appellate\ncourt upheld this ruling and the\ncase is now pending in the Ohio\nSupreme Court as a result of an\norder by Gov. C. William\nO\u2019Neill who ordered the issue\ncarried to the highest court.\nLast Feb. 1, the J&L Unit\ngained a supplemental agree\nment to its SUB provisions pro\nviding that in the event an em\nployee works part of the week\nand does not qualify for unem\nployment compensation, SUB\nwill be paid to make up the dif\nference between the employees\nearnings and 65 per cent of\ntheir average take home pay.\nw\nLocal 12 Bar Due\nTo Close 2 Weeks\nThe Local 12 bar will be\nclosed for two weeks for va\ncation, it was announced by\nPaul Leichty, bar manager.\nThe vacation period will be\nfrom June 39 to July 14.\nM\nera at the same time, for in\nstance-will multiply the op\nposition and greatly reduce\nthe chance of adopting any\nimprovement,\u201d Mr. Cole\nstated.\nWhile a county charter would\nbe a step toward solving metro\npolitan service problems of the\ncommunity, the strengthening of\ncounty government is needed,\napart from this effect, the\nLeague maintains.\nNo matter what the outcome\nof current annexation-incorpor\nation disputes, the League ex\nplains, we will still have a coun\nty government organized along\nfragmented, obsolete lines\nspending more than $16,000,000\nannually.\nLucas County First\nLucas County is the first in\nOhio moving officially to take\nadvantage of the state constitu\ntional amendment approved last\nNovember which makes it easier\nto adopt a county charter.\nActually, two matters will\nbe submitted to county voters\nthis fall\u2014the question \u201cShall\na county charter commission\nbe chosen?\" and the election\nbf charter commissioners, who\nwould serve only if the ques\ntion receives a majority fa\nvorble vote.\n(Continued on Page S)\n1\nStamps for Camp Is His Hobby\n\u2014Union Journal Photo\nElmer Chandler, 837 Clark St., retired from Spicer, is\ncrippled with arthritis and must spend most of his time\nin a chair. But he repays his union friends\u2019 kindness by\ncollecting and saving all the tax stamps he can, so some\nneedy child can have a week of fun at the Local 12 Sum- i\nmer Camp.\nDisabled Retiree Glad\nStamps Help Camp\nElmer Chandler, 837 Clark St., is back'in the Union\nJournal, this time with a success story.\nA year ago, the Journal printed a story about* Elmer,\nand how he was saving tax stamps to help send a deserving\nchild to the Local 12 Summer Camp for a week\u2019s fun.\nA lot of people who didn\u2019t\nknow Elmer read that story\nand began saving-stamps for\nhim. As a consequence, he has\nbeen able to collect many more\nstamps than he did before.\nI He\u2019s glad he\u2019s able to help,\nout, because there aren\u2019t too\nmany things he is able to do.\nCompletely crippled by arthritis\nof the spine, Elmer is unable to\nmove much of his body and must\nspend his waking hours in a\nchair. Things get pretty tire\nsome, so Elmer gets a little lift\n_ \u20141__ e _1! 11 I\nand\na\nchange by\ncounting\nthe\ntax stamps his friends have sent\nhim.\n\u201cI wish I could do a lot more,\u201d\nhe explains, \u201cbut I\u2019m glad I can\ndo even this little bit. It gives I\nme the chance to repay some of\nmy friends in the union for all\nthe wonderful things they have\ndone for me.\u201d\n\n\n\nAND IF ANYONE has any tax\nstamps around the house, says\nElmer, he will be glad to take\nthem and turn them in to the\nsummer camp.\nElmer became afflicted with'\narthritis while he was working\nat Spicer\u2019s, and struggled to keep\non the job as his condition be\ncame worse. Finally he had to\nquit in 1951.\nAlthough he was not eli\ngible for disability pension,\nmembers of the Spicer Unit\nof Local 12 UAW determined\nto help him. They kept press\ning his case until, last year,\nthey finally won a pension for\nhim from the Spicer Division.\nThis, together with a disabil\nity pension now provided by So\ncial Security, enables him to get\nalong fairly well. His wife,\nMary, helps out by doing work\nat home.\n\n\n\nMR. CHANDLER has always\nbeen active in his union's af\nfairs since coming to work at\nSpicer\u2019s in 1942. He was a stew\nard in Dept. 42-B in his plant for\ntwo years.\nHis many friends in the union\nhave responded with Christmas\nbaskets and with other help.\nAnd of course, they keep sending\nhim tax stamps for his collec\ntion.\nNeighbors keep a sharp eye\nout for stamps for Elmer. They\ninclude Ada, May and Toots\nSchwartz, 838 Oak St.; Martha\nPahup, 833 Clark St., and Earl\nLinden, a Willys worker and for\nmer neighbor.\nElmer has one deep regret. Be\ncause he cannot ride in an auto,\nhe will be unable to visit the\nsummer camp and see some of\nthe children he has helped send\nthere He has had hopes\nsome new medicine would\nhis pain enough to allow him\nthat\nease\nto\nwake the trip, but these hopes\nh\u00bbVA 3.1_i 6Y\nhave been dashed.\nueen dasned.\nSo he will keep saving stamps\nt/1 eamel __J 4\n{to send a child or two to camp,\nS-ad he can make some\ntribution to some\nlife.\ncon\nyoungster's\n1.\nUAW Strike Fund\n(Hits Record High\nOf $33 Million\nThe strike fund of the Inter\nnational Union UAW has\nf climbed to the record high of\ni nearly $33 million as of the end\nI of May, Emil Mazey, UAW\nretary-treasurer, reported.\nThis puts the Auto Workers\nin the best financial position\n(they have ever been to defend\nthemselves against the union\nbusting tactics of employers, he\nIndicated.\nsec\nThe fund balance at the end\nof April was $28,469,010. Dur\nine.May the union collected\n2418,955 in regular strike fund\ndues and $4,404,481 from the\nspecial $9 monthly dues increase.\nDuring the month $121,317 was\nspent on miscellaneous strikes.\nThat left a balance of $32..\n967,703 at the end of May.\nSpecial strike fund dues col\nlected by the big union through\nthe\n\u2014e \u2014**!rn nnuugll\nMay now total $8,093,749, Mr.\nMazey reported.\nMMMMeKKKIKNS\nJournal Now Going\nTo 2 More Locals\nTwo more local unions in\nToledo are joining the grow\ning family of Union Journal\nreaders.\nThey are Local 544 of the\nState, County and Municipal\nEmployees, and Local 48\nUAW.\nLocal 944 covers 164 em\nployers of Lucas County, while\nLocal 48 covers the 411\nem\nployees of Unitcast Corp.\nThe county employees, who\nere affiliated with Public\nEmployees District Council\nNo. 46, began receiving their\ncopy of the Journal last week.\nThis issue will be the first for\nthe members of Local 48.\nThe more than 31,000 work\ners who read the Union Jour\n\u25a0al in their homes every Fri\nday welcome these new sub\nscribers. and their news items\nand comments, will be always\nappreciated.\nMMAAA\nCost of Recession in U. S.\nPlaced at Over $50 Billion\nThe current recession will cost the nation between $50\nbillion and $80 billion depending on how long it takes to get1\nthe economy back into high-gear.\nRunning along at its current sluggish pace with little\nor no stimulus from business or government to speed re\ncovery, me economy is more;\nthan likely to chalk up the'\n$80 billion loss figure.\nThese estimates on the cost of.\nthe recession have been worked1\nout by the staff of the Joint!\nCongressional Committee on the1\nEconomic Report, which pro-'\nduces an annual survey on the\nEconomic\nReport\nsubmitted\nto\nCongress by the President.\nThe committee's loss esti\nmates came as the anti-reces\nsion program in Congress\nlimped along with minimum\nsupport from either congress\nional leaders or the Adminis\ntration.\nIt was followed by a new gov\nernment report showing that\nbusiness spending for new plant\nand equipment for 1958 have\nbeen revised downward for the I\nsecond time with the drop from!\nlast year set at 17 percent in\ncontrast to earlier estimates of\na 13 percent reduction.\nThe survey by the Commerce\nDept, and the Securities Ex\nchange Commission showed\nestimated spending of $30.7 bil-1\nlion compared to the earlier)\n'estimate of $32 billion and the;\n1957 figure of $37 billion.\nA New York Times report\nnoted in addition that \"the\ndecline in future spending\ncould be worse than the re\nport indicates.\"\nEconomists view the decline\nin business spending for new\nplant and equipment as a major\n(factor in the recession and the\nkey to speedy recovery.\nOn the employment front, the\ngovernment report of a drop in\nunemployment to 4,904,000 in\nj mid-May compared to 5,120,000\nin mid-April indicated a slight\n1 improvement.\nUnemployment Due to Rise\nBut with new additions to the\nlabor force in June as graduates\nstarted job-hunting, unemploy\nment is expected to move up\nsharply with some economists\nplacing the figure this, month\nat close to 6 million.\nWhile employment was show\ning a general gain, jobs in\nmanufacturing declined 67,000\nto a total of 15 million in May.\nAs compared with a year ago,\nmanufacturing employment is\ndown 1.7 million.\nAmong the 4.9 million un\nemployed in May, the number\nout of work 15 weeks or long\ner was estimated at 1.8 mil\nlion. There were 600,000 who\nhad been out of work for\nmore than 26 weeks.\nAverage weekly hours of fac\ntory workers were 38.8 or 1.2\nhours below a year ago.\nThe seasonally adjusted rate\nof unemployment in mid-May\nwas 7.2 percent, a drop from the\n7.5 percent in April but above\nthe March rate of 7 percent\nIn measuring the cost of the\nrecession, the congressional\ncommittee staff pegged the\nproblem on the speed of recov\nery.\nExpanding Economy Needed\nTo get back to the high em\nployment level of the pre-slump\nperiod, when unemployment was\none out of every 25 workers in\nstead of the current one out of\n14, the economy would have to\nexpand at a rate of 11 percent\u2014\na rate reached previously under\nthe stimulus of the Korean War.\nBut even at this rate, the com\nmittee staff estimates, the bill\nfor two years of slowdown and\nrecession would be more than\n$50 billion.\nIf recovery is at the slower\nrate of 7 percent\u2014the rate at\nwhich the nation recovered\nfrom the 1953-54 slump\u2014then\nthe cost will run over $79 bil\nlion by the end of 1960.\nCurrently the economy is run\nning about $35 billion a year be\nlow a high-employment level if\nfigured at a conservative growth\nrate of.3.1 percent a year\u2014the\naverage of the last 50 years.\nIf figured at a 4.7 percent rate\n\u2014a more realistic rate according\nto many leading economists\u2014the\nloss in current output would be\nfigured at 560 billion a year.\nLoss To Nation Grave\nEven if the nation recovers\nfrom the current'recession with\nunexpected speed\u2014a point\ndoubted by many economists\u2014\nthe $50 to $80 billion low would\nbe large enough to pay for a\nwide variety of essential goods\nand services.\n1\nThe loss according to the\nLasalle Election Case\nArgued Before Court\nU. S. District Court Judge Edward M. Curran took\nunder advisement arguments to determine whether he\nshould dissolve the temporary restraining order he granted\nApril 22 blocking a representation election in three Toledo\ndepartment stores or make the order permanent.\nThe National Labor Rela-i\ntions Board moved for dis\nsolution. The Retail Clerks\nInternational\nAssociation\nOP-,\nposed that and asked for a sum\nmary judgment making the or-i\nI\nder permanent.\nIn his brief filed with the\ncourt, Retail Clerks attorney:\nJoseph E. Finley contended:\nThe NLRB went ouside the\nrecord in the case to support\nits opinion;\nThe Clerks have effectively\nwithdrawn from Association\nbargaining and have never\nsought representation in a i\nthree-store unit, and j\nThe NLRB exceeded its stat-\nutory authority by placing a\nnon-complying union on the i\nballot.\nThe action in U. S. District\nCourt followed an order for an\nelection by the NLRB over the\nobjections of the Clerks. The\nNLRB overturned precedent of\nmore than 10 years standing to\norder the election petitioned for1\nby Lasalle's, Lamson\u2019s and the\nLion Store. That petition was\nfiled Nov. 20. 1957.\nThe Clerks bargained with\nthe four-store association for\nmore than six months, then won\na separate agreement after a\n1 one-day strike at Tiedtke\u2019s Nov.\n16. Led by Lasalle's, the three\nother stores petitioned for an\nelection, refused to meet further\nwith the Clerks, and claimed\nI that the Tiedtke withdrawal\nraised a question as to the\nClerks\u2019 majority status in the\nother three stores.\nNo Bargaining Session\nThe Clerks struck Lasalle\u2019s\nNov. 23 and still are picketing\nat the store which is being\nThis Week in City Councils\nCouncil Dims Hopes of Pay\nHike in 58 for Employees\nHopes of city employees for\ngetting a pay increase this year\nwere virtually extinguished by\nCity Council which again refer\nred the matter of raising funds\nto finance it to its finance com\nmittee.\nThe Council\u2019s finance com\nmittee looked into the possibili\nties of gaining increased reve\nnues a few weeks ago without\nany success.\nHowever, City Council voted\nat a special meeting Monday\nafternoon that its workers were\nentitled to a six per cent in\ncrease because of the rise in the!\ncost of living.\nJoseph Sperstad, business\nagent for the Municipal Em\nployees Union, pointed out to\nCouncil that the cost of living\nhad increased eight per cent\nsince city employees last re\nceived a wage boost in January,\n1956.\nHe noted that since then in\ncreases had been given to state\nand federal employees, as well\nas to workers in private indus\ntry and contended that an in\ncrease was justified and needed.\nAT COUNCIL\u2019S regular Mon\nday morning session, Council\nman Joseph Scalzo noted that\nthe City of Toledo for the first\nfive months of this year was\nrunning approximately $200,000\nin the red.\nDeclines in the city\u2019s payroll!\nincome tax and water revenues!\nWashington Post, would cover\nthe entire cost of the 13-year\nhighway program with about\n$15 billion left over; all the\ngoods and services the federal\ngovernment will buy thia year;\neverything sold last year by auto\ndealers, furniture, appliance.\nharware and all other hard goods\nstores; and three years of state\nand local government outlays for\nschool payrolls and buildings.\nstaffed by replacement workers.\nThe Clerks sought individual\nbargaining with the stores after\nthe Tiedtke settlement but were\nunable to crack the united front\nforced on the other stores by La\nsalle's. There has been no bar\ngaining session between the\nClerks and the Retail Associates\nsince before the Tiedtke settle\nment.\nWhen Judge Curran said in\nissuing the April 23 order that\nhe felt unions should have the\nsame right to withdraw from as\nsociation bargaining as employ\ners, the NLRB had to find new\ngrounds to support its order.\nClerks attorney* contend that\nthe NLRB used arguments made\nby the attorney for Retail Asso\ni dates in oral hearings April 8\nas a basis. This hearing, how\n'ever, is not part of the record.\nThe Clerks contend further that\nthese statement* were refuted\nby union attorney* in the same\nhearing.\nThe NLRB, in its opinion,\nstated that it rested its opinion\non the contention that the unions\nhad not actually withdrawn\nfrom multi-employer bargain\ning because their purported\nwithdrawal was not made in\ngood faith.\n\u201cSince the Board stated that\nit rested its opinion on the good\nfaith ground exclusively,\u201d wrote\nFinley in his brief for the\nunion, \"it may not, as a matter\nof law, ask this Court to sus\ntain its decision on new ground\nrules for withdrawal from mul\nti-employer bargaining which it\nsays it will appy in future cases.\nAn administrative order must\nbe judged on the basis upon\nwhich it rests.\u201d\n(Continued on Page 8)\nwere held responsible.\nCouncil at its afternoon meet\ning rejected two possible means\nof financing increases in em\nployees wage\u2014deficit financing\nand increasing the payroll tax.\nPutting the income tax increase\non the ballot, some Councilmen\ncontended, would endanger\npassage of the 1.9 mill levy for\nhighway improvements.\nCouncilman Fred Smith ar\ngued that the city pays its em\nployees more than the county.\nstate and federal governments\nfor comparable work and they\naren\u2019t justified in gaining an in\ncrease now.\nHe along with Mayor John\nW. Yagei and Councilman Max\nReddish voted against any pay\nincrease at the present time.\n\nCOUNCIL ALSO was urged\nto serve notice to the University\nof Toledo and the Board of Edu\ncation that it will no longer give\nthem city funds for their up\nkeep.\nThe city is under agreement\nto give the University of Toledo\n$900,000 in 1959 and '60 as well\nas $637,000 to the Board of Edu\ncation.\nCouncilman Jerome Jesionow\nski said that retention of these\nfunds could enable the city to\nmeet wageincreases.\nAlthough Council threw cold\nwater on hopes for a 1958 pay\nincrease, it pledged that it\nwould try to put through an in\ncrease next year.\nPlease DO NOT Patronize Lasalle\n9\n\nS\ne","height":"26760","width":"19416"}}
